I don't think it would affect my decision as much as cost does at this point in my career - as my travel funding often comes from small grants or travel allotments, ultimately keeping a low a price as possible is key for me. However, if there were multiple flights that cost nearly the same, yet had different carbon emissions that I could compare, I would definitely take it into consideration at that point. I think that the importance of carbon emissions would largely out-weight several of my other considerations, such as departure and arrival time and locations of layovers, so long as I didn't have an incredibly strict timeline. If/when my travel funding becomes less restrictive (ie hopefully as I progress in my career), I think carbon emissions would certainly weigh heavier on my decision, since price would not be as important at that point.

column15: Amtrak and BART,Drive or be driven to BART
column22: I think it would make sense to implement a personal internalized version of a carbon tax in terms of consumer preference. The values I usually see for carbon taxes are in the area of $20-50 / ton, which is why I'm relatively insensitive to differences of a couple hundred lbs CO2 - if the carbon can be mitigated for cheaper than the difference in flight costs, then choosing a more expensive greener flight is a suboptimal decision for the environment. Carbon pricing schemes often price emissions between $10 and $100 / ton. On this logic, the cheaper flight usually makes more sense. The 'greenest' action would be to purchase the cheaper flight and donate the saved funds to a carbon mitigation effort.

Some departments do not have the luxury of a well-padded budget to select more expensive flights, even if that means lower CO2 emissions. As a private citizen, seeing the CO2 emissions would actually help me select flights and be more mindful about my travel. I could see myself selecting flights that are slightly higher in price but lower in CO2 emissions. Of course, other factors come into play such as flight departure location and non-stop options. Closer and non-stop are my preferences. Anyway, if departments supported the purchase of flights that had lower CO2 emissions but were more expensive then I would definitely take that route (no pun intended!).

column15: Drive or be driven to BART
column22: Typically, I do not factor carbon emissions into my travel arrangements. I do factor in whether a flight is non-stop, the time of the flights, and layover length. Unless it is exorbitantly over priced ($200+), I will almost alway opt for a non-stop flight out of SMF, followed by a less expensive layover flight out of SMF, followed by a non-stop or layover flight out of SFO. It was very hard to choose a realistic flight without knowing how long the layovers might be.
